:INFO
Milk Kefir Troubleshooting
Kefir grains are robust but respond to changes in milk, temperature, and handling. Most problems resolve within a few batches.

:PATH
Kefir Is Too Thin After 24 Hours
Grains may need time to adjust — use more grains or fewer milk.
|
:INFO
Kefir Is Too Thin After 24 Hours
New grains or recently refrigerated grains need 2 to 3 activation batches before producing consistently thick kefir. Increase the grain-to-milk ratio (more grains per cup of milk) or reduce the milk volume. Warmer room temperature also speeds fermentation and thickens the result. If grains are new, discard the first few batches and persist — they will activate.

:PATH
Kefir Tastes Too Sour
Over-fermented — reduce time or use more milk per tablespoon of grains.
|
:INFO
Kefir Tastes Too Sour
Over-fermentation produces a sharp, yogurt-like sourness. Reduce fermentation time by 4 to 6 hours. Alternatively, use more milk per tablespoon of grains — a thinner ratio means longer fermentation is needed to reach the same pH. In summer, move to an air-conditioned room or reduce the grain-to-milk ratio.

:PATH
Grains Are Slimy or Pink
Contamination — source new grains immediately.
|
:INFO
Grains Are Slimy or Pink
Healthy grains are white, slightly rubbery, and smell sour-milky. Pink or red coloration indicates contamination from an external organism, most likely Serratia marcescens or a mold. Do not use contaminated grains. Source fresh grains from a reliable supplier. Sterilize all equipment before starting again.

:NOTE
Chlorinated Water Harms Grains
Never rinse grains under chlorinated tap water — the chlorine kills beneficial bacteria in the colony over time. If you must rinse grains, use filtered water or milk. Most grains do not need rinsing at all.
